<TITLE> Iraq forms committee after prisoner abuse reports </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BAGHDAD, Thu Jun 18, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Iraqi government formed a committee on Thursday to investigate reports that prisoners face systematic torture and abuse, including rape, in the war-torn country's often overcrowded and decrepit prisons. The committee would consist of officials from the ministries of defense, interior, justice, labor and human rights, and would work with parliament's human rights committee to check into prison conditions that have sparked protests by inmates. "The government will not tolerate anybody who harms national efforts to build security institutions of international standards," government spokesman Ali al-Dabbagh said in a statement. Most of Iraq's jails are run down and badly overcrowded and the release into Iraqi custody this year of thousands of people held by the US military since its 2003 invasion is putting further strain on the system. This week, jailed supporters of anti-American Shia cleric Moqtada al-Sadr staged a partial hunger strike to try to draw attention to their plight. International rights groups have urged the government to clean up its prisons, ensure that people accused of crimes are brought before judges quickly, and end widespread torture. Iraq's judicial council said on Thursday it would increase the number of judges and prosecutors assigned to the Sadrist prisoners and other detainees in the same jail, and ordered them to work extra hours to deal with all the cases. Prisoners complain that they can wait a year before being brought before a j
